1. 14· vt ponderi respondeant, ‘so that they may balance the weight.’ 240 heavy pennies would weigh more than a pound, the same number of light pennies less.

1. 16. quod si numerus . . ., ‘but if the 20 shillings (by weight) on being counted come to 6d. or more, more than a pound, the money is judged unworthy to be accepted? The Chamberlain weighs. out as many pence as will balance the standard pound: these are then counted and if there are more than 246 the money is rejected. This treatment only applies to payments made numero. Payments of farm which have to be assayed are treated differently.

1. 24. examen quod vulgo essaium dicitur, ‘the test commonly called the assay.‘ Here as usual the author endeavours to substitute the classical word.

1. 27, examinati . . . fiant. The Treasurer's clerk and the Chamberlains are to put away separately the lumps of silver obtained in the assay, and the pennies paid in as the farm. Being of silver of known standard they will serve for plate or for coinage for the king's foreign possessions.
